																		Re: Mandala-Manifested Meadow of Majestic, Melancholic Madness
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/uraniumempire" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1613974); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1613974&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204973" alt="UraniumEmpire" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1613974)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/uraniumempire" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1613974); return false;" >UraniumEmpire</a></span> <span class="odate time_1609983128 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Jan 2021 01:32</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4864004">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Crit&nbsp;lives&nbsp;within</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<h2><span><strong>Coherence:</strong></span></h2>
<p>Assuming you meant thematic coherence (due to the Understandability section), this article is a bit all over the place. The nuns, the worms, the mass hysteria, etc., none of it feels like it's properly fit together. Moreover, the Mandala's usage feels largely superficial, especially considering that it felt like a Hindu concept was being forced into a largely Christian framework.</p>
<h2><span><strong>Consistency</strong></span></h2>
<p>Everything from the tulpa onward feels as if it's missing context. The stakes necessary for it to work simply aren't there for much of the piece, and it leads to what feels like a slog through events that don't carry any emotional weight.</p>
<h2><span><strong>Dialogue</strong></span></h2>
<p>Dialogue was alright. Only thing of note was that I found it odd:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Operator: Indeed. The phone says that this fluid's effects include but are not limited to:<br />
1.) Loss of inhibitions.<br />
2.) Steady increase in psychosis-type symptoms.<br />
3.) Dizziness.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Having a character suddenly speak in list form feels off.</p>
<h2><span><strong>Clinical tone</strong></span></h2>
<p>It was fine.</p>
<h2><span><strong>Pacing</strong></span></h2>
<p>The pacing is incredibly off. By the IV portion, the piece read like it was near the end, despite being only 1/3rd the way through. It made the chase scene a major slog. Then the dream ends, and it cuts to the second offset, which feels almost entirely disconnected from the events I read in the log. It's for this reason among others that I recommend removing the second offset.</p>
<p>Additionally, how the &quot;FOOTAGE LOST&quot;s break up sections is very disorientating. It leaves a lot of the earlier sections feeling cut off from one another, without a sense of continuity.</p>
<h2><span><strong>Plot</strong></span></h2>
<p>It didn't seem very good.</p>
<p>As noted above, the piece fails to establish the emotional stakes. I don't know who Hero is; I don't know who the <em>tulpa</em> is. Because I as the reader have no real understanding of these characters, I'm not able to care about everything happening to them. The end result is that the plot feels like a slog through a list of things occurring to characters I neither know or care for.</p>
<p>Additionally, none of the plot feels like it's thematically connected to the anomaly at hand. This is a piece about someone attempting to rescue their tulpa from the dreamscape for a good chunk; however, the overarching &quot;eldritch sponge&quot; aspect barely comes up, and it's only really explored in what amounts to a (figurative) footnote in the final offset. This is especially bad as I heavily recommend you <em>remove</em> it for pacing, among other things.</p>
<h2><span><strong>Understandability</strong></span></h2>
<p>I could understand what was happening perfectly fine, up until the final offset. I don't have any advice on how to fix said offset's understandability, as again, I heavily recommend you remove it.</p>
<h2><span><strong>Is the second list-page even necessary, or can I just remove it and shove the plot reveal into the main page via a collapsible?</strong></span></h2>
<p>100% remove it. It feels overly expository, and the note at the end is unnecessary.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<h2><span>Overall</span></h2>
<p>This piece needs extensive restructuring if it wants to work. The thematics don't feel consistent, the piece feels like it's ending a third of the way through, and the characters don't make enough of an impression to justify the plot of the log.</p>

							</div>

